To create a TikZ LaTeX diagram for the described graph \( P_{2m} \), we can represent it as a path with 2m vertices where the middle m-1 vertices each have two neighbors (forming a chain), and the endpoints \( v_0 \) and \( v_{2m-1} \) each have only one neighbor.

Here is the TikZ LaTeX code to generate this graph:

```latex
\documentclass{standalone}
\usepackage{tikz}

\begin{document}
\begin{tikzpicture}[node distance=1cm]

% Define nodes
\node (v0) at (0,0) [circle, draw] {};
\node (v1) at (1,0) [circle, draw] {};
\node (v2) at (2,0) [circle, draw] {};
\node (vm1) at (m-1,0) [circle, draw] {};
\node (vm) at (m,0) [circle, draw] {};
\node (v2m1) at (2*m-1,0) [circle, draw] {};

% Draw edges
\draw (v0) -- (v1);
\foreach \i in {1,...,m-2} {
    \draw (vm-\i) -- (vm-\i+1);
}
\draw (vm) -- (vm1);
\draw (vm1) -- (v2m1);

\end{tikzpicture}
\end{document}
```

Explanation:
- We define nodes for each vertex \( v_i \) from \( v_0 \) to \( v_{2m-1} \).
- We use a loop to connect the middle m-1 vertices \( v_1 \) through \( v_{2m-2} \) such that each has exactly two neighbors.
- We manually connect the endpoints \( v_0 \) and \( v_{2m-1} \) to their respective neighbors \( v_1 \) and \( v_{2m-2} \).

This code will produce a visual representation of the graph \( P_{2m} \) with the specified properties. Adjust the value of `m` in your LaTeX document to change the number of vertices in the path.

